# Q-SYS Lua Script Architecture

## 0. Core Philosophy

> **"Lean code + rich debug output."**
> Every significant action, state change, and interaction must be logged.
> An empty debug window is a useless one.

**Target metrics when refactoring:**

- 50–70% line reduction from verbose implementations (more is fine if clarity is preserved)
- Script stays under ~1000 lines for most controllers
- Every user interaction visible in the debug console

### 0.1 Complexity tiers (micro vs full controller)

**Lean code** and **rich debug** scale with script complexity. Checklist items in §4 and §9 are **not** one-size-fits-all.

|                          | **Micro-controller** | **Full controller** |
|--------------------------|----------------------|---------------------|
| **Typical scope**        | Few fixed `Component.New(...)` references, no discovery, load-once | Component selectors, `GetComponents()` discovery, many handlers/rooms, or hot-reload / rebind |
| **Init logging**         | One summary line (room name, debug flag) + optional single "Ready" line; phase markers optional | Phase markers + configuration line as in §4.3 |
| **Setup / discovery**    | **Aggregate** counts and **errors only**; skip per-item "OK" lines unless diagnosing | Per-item discovery logging where operators need to see each device |
| **Registration**         | One line with **totals** | Per-handler-type counts |
| **Source attribution**   | Keep on significant actions; wording can be shorter | Full `(Source: ...)` on state changes |
| **`validateControls`**   | Omit or inline `return true` when there are no script-level `Controls.*` | Required when controls are validated |
| **`cleanup` / teardown** | Optional for load-once scripts; required if handlers are reattached at runtime | Use `cleanupComponentHandlers` when swapping components |
| **Public API table**     | Only if another script calls into this file | As needed for cross-script access |

**Principle:** The **shortest** script that stays clear and adequately logged — not the same ceremony as a 900-line matrix controller.

---

## 1. No OOP / Class Pattern

**OOP must never be used.** Every Q-SYS control script is a **singleton by nature** — one script context, one set of `Controls.*`, one set of `Component.GetComponents()` results. There is never more than one instance per file.

**Do not use** `setmetatable`, `__index`, `.new()`, `self:`, or `self.` — they add ceremony with no benefit here.

```lua
-- ❌ AVOID
MyController = {}
MyController.__index = MyController
function MyController.new() return setmetatable({}, MyController) end
function MyController:setRoute(input, output) ... end

-- ✅ CORRECT — flat module, local state
local components = { router = nil, invalid = {} }
local state      = { power = false }

local function setRoute(input, output, source) ... end
```

---

## 2. Standard File Structure

Follow this section order in every script:

```text
[ Header comment ]    -- name, author, version, brief description
[ Configuration ]     -- data tables: room maps, preset lists, device lists
[ Controls ]          -- local controls = { name = Controls.name, ... }
[ Utilities ]         -- only helpers actually used (see §3)
[ Config ]            -- roomName, debug, clearString constants
[ State ]             -- components {}, state {}, and any per-script flags
[ Debug ]             -- local function debugPrint(str)
[ Functions ]         -- all local functions in dependency order (callees before callers)
[ Events ]            -- local function registerEvents()
[ Init ]              -- local function init()
[ Public API ]        -- GlobalName = { exposed functions } for cross-script calls
[ Start ]             -- pcall wrapper that calls init()
```

---

## 3. Utility Functions (include what you use)

The block below is the **standard toolkit**, not a mandatory paste into every file.

- Include **`bind`** in scripts that assign `EventHandler`
- Include **`setProp`**, **`isArr`**, and **`bindArray`** when needed for control properties or arrays
- Include **`cleanupComponentHandlers`** when swapping components that have handlers
- **Omit** helpers you do not use

```lua
local function isArr(t)
    return type(t) == "table" and t ~= nil[1]
end

-- Guards against redundant writes, feedback loops, and race conditions
local function setProp(ctrl, prop, val)
    if not ctrl or ctrl[prop] == val then return end
    ctrl[prop] = val
end

local function bind(ctrl, handler)
    if not ctrl or not handler then return false end
    local ok = pcall(function() ctrl.EventHandler = handler end)
    return ok
end

local function bindArray(ctrls, handler)
    if not ctrls or not handler then return 0 end
    local array = isArr(ctrls) and ctrls or { ctrls }
    local count = 0
    for i, ctrl in ipairs(array) do
        if bind(ctrl, function(ctl)
            local ok, err = pcall(handler, i, ctl)
            if not ok then print("Handler error [index " .. i .. "]: " .. tostring(err)) end
        end) then
            count = count + 1
        end
    end
    return count
end

local function cleanupComponentHandlers(oldComps, controlNames, debugCb)
    if not oldComps or not controlNames then return 0 end
    local cleaned = 0
    for _, name in ipairs(controlNames) do
        if oldComps[name] and oldComps[name].EventHandler then
            oldComps[name].EventHandler = nil
            cleaned = cleaned + 1
        end
    end
    if debugCb and cleaned > 0 then
        debugCb("Cleaned up " .. cleaned .. " handlers from old components")
    end
    return cleaned
end
```

**Why `setProp()` matters:** Prevents redundant Q-SYS control updates, guards against feedback loops, and helps avoid race conditions.

